        "title": "#ShareGoodness Debrief",
        "start": "12:00",
        "end": "12:30",
        "description": "Objectives:\n• Debrief experiences with sharing goodness and taking charge of technology.\n• Learn principles of creating a positive online presence.\n• Create a video with your company.\n\nPreparation—Throughout the Week:\nRemind youth throughout the week of their “Taking Charge of Technology” plan, and encourage them to participate in the #ShareGoodness challenge.\n\nTime Frame:\n#ShareGoodness discussion: 12:00–12:15 p.m.\nCompany video: 12:15–12:30 p.m.\n\n#ShareGoodness Debrief Format\n\nDiscussion (15 minutes):\nInvite the youth to share experiences they had sharing goodness and following their “Taking Charge of Technology” plan.\n\nUse the following questions to lead the youth in a discussion about using technology to share goodness, based on the following three principles from Elder Bednar:\n\n“Beginning at this place on this day, I exhort you to sweep the earth with messages filled with righteousness and truth—messages that are authentic, edifying, and praiseworthy—and literally to sweep the earth as with a flood.”\n—David A. Bednar, “To Sweep the Earth as with a Flood” (Brigham Young University Education Week devotional, Aug. 19, 2014).\n\nAuthentic—Genuine:\n• What does it mean to be authentic?\n• What does authenticity look like on social media or other digital communication?\n• Share an example of a post or account that effectively shows authenticity. Some youth may pull up a post or account on their phones and share.\n• What happens when we follow a lot of people who share only the picture-perfect parts of their life?\n\n“A person or product that is not authentic is false, fake, and fraudulent. Our messages should be truthful, honest, and accurate. We should not exaggerate, embellish, or pretend to be someone or something we are not. Our content should be trustworthy and constructive.”\n—David A. Bednar, “To Sweep the Earth as with a Flood” (Brigham Young University Education Week devotional, Aug. 19, 2014).\n\nEdifying—Providing Moral or Intellectual Instruction:\n• Have you ever been impacted by a positive, uplifting post or text from a friend? Someone may pull up an example on their phone to share.\n• What kinds of posts or interactions are most edifying to you?\n• What accounts can you follow to get more edifying content?\n• How can we reduce bullying and arguing online?\n\n“Brothers and sisters, share the gospel with genuine love and concern for others. Be courageous and bold but not overbearing in sustaining and defending our beliefs, and avoid contention.”\n—David A. Bednar, “To Sweep the Earth as with a Flood” (Brigham Young University Education Week devotional, Aug. 19, 2014).\n\nPraiseworthy—Deserving Approval and Admiration:\n• What does it mean for our use of technology to be praiseworthy? Think before you post or text. Make sure posts and comments are appropriate.\n• How can you be careful not to post or text something you’ll regret?\n• Is there anyone you know of who suffered from posting or texting something without thinking first?\n\n“If there is anything virtuous, lovely, or of good report or praiseworthy, we seek after these things.”\n—Articles of Faith 1:13\n\nCompany Video (15 minutes):\nMake a video that will help the company share what they have learned while at FSY. You may have your youth get in a circle or a line and go from youth to youth, filming them for 10 seconds each as they respond to the question “How has your experience in the past week affected your life for good?” Or you can ask, “What do you want to take home with you from FSY?”\n\nYou can ask your youth if they have any other ideas for making a video that will help them make and remember the goals they have chosen. Ask for a youth volunteer to film the video and share it with everyone else. If there are youth without phones, they can do this by posting their video online and collecting emails from the other participants to share the link. The whole company will then have access to the video they made together.",
